</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-AssociationPractice">
  <title> Association Practice Problems </title>
<p> For each problem,. </p> 

<p> <term> Olympic Medals</term></p> 
    <p>
      A sports analyst wants to know whether the type of medal won at the
      2024 Paris Olympics was independent of country for five countries
      with the most total medals. The top five countries by total medals were
      the United States, China, Great Britain, France, and Australia.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>2024 Paris Olympics Medal Counts for Five Countries</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell><term>Country</term></cell>
          <cell><term>Gold</term></cell>
          <cell><term>Silver</term></cell>
          <cell><term>Bronze</term></cell>
          <cell><term>Total</term></cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>United States</cell><cell>40</cell><cell>44</cell><cell>42</cell><cell>126</cell></row>
        <row><cell>China</cell><cell>40</cell><cell>27</cell><cell>24</cell><cell>91</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Great Britain</cell><cell>14</cell><cell>22</cell><cell>29</cell><cell>65</cell></row>
        <row><cell>France</cell><cell>16</cell><cell>26</cell><cell>22</cell><cell>64</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Australia</cell><cell>18</cell><cell>19</cell><cell>16</cell><cell>53</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Total</cell><cell>128</cell><cell>138</cell><cell>133</cell><cell>399</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p> 
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether medal type
      (gold, silver, or bronze) is independent of country.
    </p>
<exercise xml:id="ex-chisquare-independence-OlympicMedals">
<title> Olympic Medals</title>
  <statement>
  <p> At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether medal type (gold, silver, or bronze) is independent of country. Include the hypotheses, expected values table, chi-square test and p-value, and the conclusion in context. </p>
  </statement>
    <solution> <title> Hypotheses</title> 
    <p>  This is a chi-square test of independence. Although the sample is not random, there are 5 in each category. We could have selected 5 random countries, but not all countries had at least five medals.
    </p>
    <p> The hypotheses are: </p>
    <p><m>H_0:</m> Medal type and country are independent. </p>
    <p><m>H_a:</m> Medal type and country are dependent. </p>
    </solution>
  <solution> <title> Expected Values</title> 
  <p> Compute the expected counts for each using the totals:
      <md>
        E=\dfrac{(\text{row total})(\text{column total})}{\text{grand total}}.
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The row totals are <m>126</m>, <m>91</m>, <m>65</m>, <m>64</m>, and
      <m>53</m>. The column totals are <m>128</m> gold, <m>138</m> silver,
      and <m>133</m> bronze, with grand total <m>399</m>.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Expected Counts</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Country</cell>
          <cell>Gold</cell>
          <cell>Silver</cell>
          <cell>Bronze</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>United States</cell><cell><m>40.42</m></cell><cell><m>43.60</m></cell><cell><m>42.01</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>China</cell><cell><m>29.19</m></cell><cell><m>31.49</m></cell><cell><m>30.33</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Great Britain</cell><cell><m>20.85</m></cell><cell><m>22.49</m></cell><cell><m>21.67</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>France</cell><cell><m>20.53</m></cell><cell><m>22.13</m></cell><cell><m>21.34</m></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Australia</cell><cell><m>17.01</m></cell><cell><m>18.34</m></cell><cell><m>17.67</m></cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
</solution>
  <solution> <title> Statistical Test</title> 
    <p> Next compute the test statistic using each cell:
      <md>\chi^2=\sum \dfrac{(O-E)^2}{E}</md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using the observed and expected counts, the chi-square test statistic is
      <m>\chi^2 \approx 12.65</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The degrees of freedom using the 5 country rows and 3 medal columns as
      <md>df=(r-1)(c-1)=(5-1)(3-1)=8</md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For a chi-square distribution with <m>8</m> degrees of freedom, the
      <m>p</m>-value is approximately <m>0.125</m>.
    </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Chi-square Test on TI-84 </title> 
<p> As you can see, there is a lot of computation with this test. But the good news is that technology can help us out. We will be creating a matrix in the calculator so it can compute the expected values for us. </p>
<p> Find the MATRIX above the [X-1] button. </p>
<p>Press [2nd] [X-1] for the Matrix, use the arrow to the right twice for EDIT menu, we are going to select matrix  <term>1: A </term> and press [ENTER]. </p>
<p>We need to identify the size of the matrix, input 5 rows (across/horizontal) x 3 columns (down/vertical) and then input the observed data by hitting [ENTER] after each entry. </p>
 <figure xml:id="ChiSquareOlympics3">
            <caption>Building data matrix in calculator</caption>
            <image source="ChiMedal3.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>create 5x3 matrix.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 
<p> Next, we will perform the hypothesis test. </p>
<p>Press [STAT] button and arrow twice to the right for the TESTS menu and scroll down to option <term>C: <m>\chi^2</m>-Test  </term> and press [ENTER] to select it.</p>
<p>Identify where the observed matrix is [A] and the expected matrix is [B] which the calculator will calculate for you. Scroll to <term> Calculate </term> and press [ENTER] to perform the test. </p>
  <figure xml:id="ChiSquareOlympic4">
            <caption>Chi-square test in calculator</caption>
            <image source="ChiMedal4.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>select option C for chi-square test. Test value =12.647 and p=0.125</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 
<p> The  statistical tests value is <m>\chi^2 = 12.647</m> and p-value of <m>p=0.125</m> with 8 degrees of freedom.
</p>
</solution> 
  <solution> <title> Conclusion</title> 
    <p>
      Since <m>p \gt 0.05</m>, we do not reject <m>H_0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is not sufficient evidence at the 0.05 significance level to
      conclude that medal type won was dependent on the country for the 2024 Olympics.
    </p>
    <p>
      In context, this means the proportion of gold, silver, and bronze
      medals was the same across the United States, China, Great Britain,
      France, and Australia (based on the totals for that country).
    </p>
  </solution>

</exercise>

